* {{note label|Note|e|e}} Robert Forczyk (2014) wrote that the 12th Mechanized Crops had 725 tanks available, of which were 483 T-26 and 242 BT's.{{Sfn|Forczyk|2014|p=30}}
* {{note label|Note|f|f}}On entering the Soviet Union in [[Operation Barbarossa]] the [[6th Panzer Division]] had a total of 235–245 tanks, which consisted of about 47 [[Panzer II]]s, 155 [[Panzer 35(t)]]s, 30 [[Panzer IV]]s, 5 Panzerbef 35(t)s (command tanks) and 8 Panzerbefs.<ref>{{cite web |title=6th Panzer Division, Order of Battle of 22 June, 1941 |url=http://www.2ndbn5thmar.com/history/6thPzDiv1941.pdf |publisher= |accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref>
* {{note label|Note|g|g}}The tanks were eventually destroyed by [[Artillery battery|batteries]] of [[88 mm gun|88mm flak guns]] and [[Field artillery|100mm artillery guns]] employed in an [[Anti-tank warfare|anti-tank]] role.{{Sfn|Raus|2003|pp=24{{endash}}25}}
* {{note label|Note|h|h}}[[Kampfgruppe]] [[Erhard Raus|Raus]] consisted of Panzer Regiment 11, one [[battalion]] of the 4th [[Motorized infantry]] [[Regiment]], the 2nd [[Battalion]]s of the 76th [[Field artillery|Artillery]] [[Regiment]], one company of [[Combat engineering|Panzer Engineer]] [[Battalion]] 57, one company from [[Panzerjäger]] [[Battalion]] 41, one [[Artillery battery|battery]] of the 2nd [[Battalion]] [[Anti-aircraft warfare|Flak]] [[Regiment]] 411 and Motorcycle [[Battalion]] 6 (afternoon).{{sfn|Raus|2003|p=13}}
* {{note label|Note|i|i}}On 11 July 1941 Colonel P Poluboiarov, [[Northwestern Front]] armoured directorate, reported that the [[3rd Mechanised Corps (Soviet Union)|3rd Mechanised Corps]] had "completely perished" having only 400 men remaining who escaped encirclement with 2nd Tank Division and only 1 [[BT-8|BT-7]] tank. German Sources reported the destruction of more than 200 tanks, including 29 [[KV tank|KV-1s]], 150 guns and hundreds of trucks and other vehicles. The 5th Tank Division was at [[Yelnya]] by 4 July 1941 and consisted of 2,552 men and a total of two [[BT-7]] tanks and four armoured cars. It was destroyed at the [[Battle of Białystok–Minsk]].{{sfn|Glantz|1998|p=126}}
* {{note label|Note|j|j}}Colonel Grinberg temporary commander of the [[12th Mechanized Corps (Soviet Union)|12th Mechanized Corps]] after the death of his corps' original commander Major General Shestopalov, reported on 29 July that the strength of his corps had fallen to under 17,000 men after the first two weeks of combat.{{sfn|Glantz |1998|p=128}}
